skillful pilot known for her courage and daring. After

guished Flying Cross, awarded by the U.S. Congress.
Her ambition was realized at dusk on May 20, 1932,
when her small Lockheed monoplane lifted off the
runway at Harbour Grace, Newfoundland. Two
equipment malfunctions and a fierce storm made the
nighttime flight especially hazardous. At dawn, Ame-
lia sought to bring the plane down on the first avail-
able land. It turned out to be a pasture near Derry,
Ireland, where she landed 14 hours and 56 minutes
after take-off.
Mint Stamp: The mint stamp on this Cover was issued
by the United States in 1963. It pictures the famous
aviator standing in front of her Lockheed Electra air-
plane, the plane in which she later vanished in a
daring flight across the Pacific.
Postmark: This Cover was postmarked in Harbour
Grace, Newfoundland on May 20, 1984, the anniver-
sary of Amelia Earhart's take-off on her transatlantic
adventure.

properties.sfomuseum:description: Airmail flight cover, part of International Tributes to the History of Flight series by the Postal Commemorative Society; white envelope with full color illustration cachet and inset stamp commemorating first woman to fly the Atlantic on May 20, 1932, in Harbour Grace, Newfoundland, by Amelia Earhart with Lockheed Vega monoplane; cancellation stamp dated May 20, 1984 in Harbour Grace; includes information on reverse.
